    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-03-20T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-03-20T11:00:00-05:00" n="51"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d51">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.60F/37a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Carr</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-03-20T11:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 20, 1939—11 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>19. In view of the situation as set forth in your telegram of March 17th, you are
                    directed to close the Legation at Praha;<note n="90" xml:id="d51fn90">The
                        Minister in Czechoslovakia reported in telegram No. 61, March 21, 5 p.m.:
                        “The Legation closed today as instructed”. (124.60F/38)</note> to turn over
                    the Government building, property and archives to the Consulate <pb facs="0068"
                        n="56" xml:id="pg_56"/> General; and at your convenience to leave Praha. A
                    separate message containing detailed administrative instructions will be sent
                        you.<note n="91" xml:id="d51fn91">Telegram No. 20, March 20, noon, not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The President has requested me to express to you his particular appreciation of
                    the highly distinguished service you have rendered the Government as Minister to
                    Czechoslovakia. I desire also in the name of the Secretary of State as well as
                    in my own to evidence our recognition of the exceptional work you have done
                    under circumstances of peculiar difficulty. The services you have rendered are a
                    matter of pride to the entire Foreign Service with which you have been closely
                    connected over a period of so many years.</p>
                <p>I am giving this telegram, together with your March 17th, to the press at noon
                    today.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
